article.description: Two great games by Brent Barry gave the Sonics consecutive wins for the first time in nearly two months.
article.headline: Barry scores season-high 28 for Sonics
article.linkText: Sonics get first consecutive wins in 24 games
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Brent Barry doesn't put much stock in Seattle's two-game winning streak. Barry scored a season-high 28 points, Ray Allen added 27 and the Seattle SuperSonics beat the Atlanta Hawks 118-110 Tuesday night to win two straight for the first time in 25 games. "We've beaten two teams that have been struggling all year long," Barry said. "We can't get excited about beating those kinds of teams." The Sonics improved to 4-1 in their last five games in Atlanta, but Seattle entered with just one victory in seven games and three of 14 overall. "I missed six weeks with a broken hand," said Barry, who returned from the injured list last week. "These last two games are the only legitimate chances I've had to play. I don't know what the doctor put in my hand, but it's working. I think I have a little bionic motion." Stephen Jackson scored 39 points for the Hawks, who have lost six of seven. Jackson, who has at least 30 in three of five games, hit four straight free throws on consecutive possessions to cut the lead to 99-93 with 6:11 remaining. Barry, who scored 25 points in a 115-101 victory Saturday at Orlando, had 17 points in the second quarter, as many as the Hawks. He went 4-of-5 on 3-pointers. Barry didn't score again until his straightaway 3 made it 107-99 with 3:20 remaining. He added a final 3 at the 2:11 mark before hitting a pair of free throws that built the lead back to eight with 53.6 seconds left. "He was going three, four feet behind the 3-point line, knocking shots down at the end of the shot clock sometimes," Atlanta guard Bob Sura said. "Nothing you can do about that. But overall they shot the ball well from the 3-point line, which hurt us." Reserve swingman Vladimir Radmanovic had 16 points, including a 3-pointer with 4:37 left that put Seattle up 104-96. Allen, who tied Reggie Evans with a team-high 10 rebounds, was 11-of-12 from the free throw line. Sonics coach Nate McMillan thought his players had a defensive lapse in the third quarter as Seattle let a 16-point lead drop to three on Jackson's 3-pointer at the end of the period. "We need to put teams away," McMillan said. "We allowed them to get back in the game. When a team looks like it's going in or giving up, we need to bury them." Jackson hit a 3 from the right side of the key at the 2:37 mark that cut the lead to 107-104, but Atlanta drew no closer. Sura scored 19 points, but he committed two of his four turnovers in the fourth quarter and his reverse layup rimmed out with 1:25 remaining and the Hawks down four. He blamed the loss on Atlanta's terrible second quarter. "We gave up 40-some points," Sura said. "It's too hard when you keep fighting to play from behind." Jason Terry had 18 points on 5-of-19 shooting. He missed all seven 3-point attempts. Hawks coach Terry Stotts watched his team fall to 1-25 when allowing 100 points. "They went to a zone in the second quarter and we stopped moving, stopped passing the ball," Stotts said. "It broke our rhythm. We fouled too much, so we put them on the free throw line and they were able to drop back in their zone. We lost our confidence because of the momentum swing and just the whole tone of the game changed."

Game notes
Barry, who finished with a game-high nine assists, has gone 13-of-17 on 3-pointers the last two games. ... Terry has shot 20.8 percent (5-of-17) on 3s the last four games. ... The Hawks play Wednesday at Dallas, where they haven't won since 1997 and lost 105-79 last year. Atlanta beat the Mavericks 102-96 last month, the Hawks' final game before Shareef Abdur-Rahim and Theo Ratliff were traded to Portland. ... Seattle became the 10th opponent to score at least 100 points in the Hawks' last 13 games.
